description.text: This has been created with my new PLA gear kit, which includes parametric PLA compatible pin connectors. With this new OpenSCAD kit, the gear centre and pins remain the same, its only the outer shells that change. It will allow the creation of all sorts of gear object mashups.

If you have a Replicator 1/2/2X all you need to download and print is the centre_plate, pin_plate and full_plate. They already have helper tabs, so they are ready to slice. I kept the center and pins separate so you can print them in a different colour, which I personally think looks better =) If you have a smaller printer you can print the small_plate and plate2 four times, instead of the full_plate. The blue cube gear I printed above used 25% infill, and 3 shells (2 extra shells in ReplicatorG) at a 200 micron layer height with the skin module enabled.

comments.text: I like the rounded edges, they give it a much cleaner look. Also, I don't have problems turning the mechanism but then I mostly print with ABS and it's much easier to clean up. I've recently been experimenting with some of the carbon filaments and the results are awesome and this would be just brilliant printed with that, or even T Glase.

description.text: This is my new OpenSCAD PLA gear kit. The pin connectors are specially designed to work with PLA - so they are flexible and don't crack when inserted. The idea of this kit is that the gear centre and pins remain the same, its only the outer shells that change. This makes individual gear plates interchangeable, which should simplify the creation of all sorts of gear object mashups. Have fun! UPDATE Aug, 31 2013 Having problems with loose pins with some PLA colors? I have added some slightly thinker pin plates to solve this problem one has 0.2mm thicker diameter, the other 0.4mm.

The main variable you need to change is object_file in the SCAD source file. This changes the STL source used to create the outer shell. The outer shell stl object should be around 50mm square, however you can use the object_scale variable to make adjustments as need be. Uncomment individual module calls up at the top of the file to check the behaviour. Once the stl object scale and position are correct, use make all on the command line to batch build all the plates in one go. The makefile is set up for OpenSCAD on the mac. If you are running windows, change the SCAD variable in the Makefile to the appropriate path.

description.header: NOTE: OpenSCAD is pretty fussy about the STL objects it will accept, they need to be centred on the origin (0,0,0) and well formed.

description.text: Teach your students how to model simple 3d objects, and neatly tuck away the myriad cords tangling on the floor, both at the same time!

The base is a sketched rectangle, with the bottom line switched to construction mode; then a circle is added of arbitrary radius tangent to the bottom, also in construction mode. To that add a non-construction arc of angle 180 touching the construction circle and two lines of equal length connecting it to the bottom line, then two lines connecting those bottoms to the original rectangle's corners. Constrain the distance from the left and top arbitrarily (I ran a line from the centerpoint of the arc to the top of the arc and then from that point to touching the top line of the original rectangle, but there's probably a better way), pad to an arbitrary width, then rotate the view to the top and sketch a hole centered in the side without a tunnel going through it. Punch that hole through, then fillet and chamfer to taste.
For Clip 2, add to the original rectangle before making the original "right" line a construction line, then repeat much of the original process to add a second "tunnel". Remember to fully constrain your sketch!

Objectives Students will learn how to 3d print useful primitive objects, and your classroom will be tidy and safer from trip hazards Audiences Elementary students with a rudementary knowledge of computers should be able to do this with some effort - when I was in 5th grade I had to memorize all 50 states and their capitals, as well as draw it on a blank map, so this seems easier. Preparation Flag all cords that are not properly anchored but that do not require slack to operate (you might want to anchor the projector's cord but not the laptop or mouse's cord); check with school maintenance for what size anchoring hardware they prefer to use (they might need a bigger mounting hole). Accurate measurement tools will also be necessary - if calipers are not available, they can be printed from this site (flat, soft, and non-conductive calipers are safest!) Steps!
  • Give each student, or group of students, a set of cords to anchor and any other requirements.
  • The students then model the clip
  • Students work with the teacher to print the clip
  • Maintenance then installs the clip
    • Results See Objectives - your students learn how to make clips, and your classroom gets tidier and safer. For grading, you could do this quite early in the year and deduct points if any of the clips fail by the year's end.

A little work in progress, this 'shellter' was designed after hearing hermit crabs inhabiting shotgun shells.  So I thought that, the best way to make an artificial shell, is to make something that we already know hermit crabs inhabit that is man made, and thus the "Shotgun Shellter" was born.  With the little ridges I find in most shotguns, the metal 'lip' on the back, but added a slight curve so it would easily conform to the cuved abdomen of the crab.  At the moment the object itself is very small and needs to be resized for the hermit crab in question, but you probably need to resize it for your particular hermit crab anyway.
Future Designs-  Probably going to introduce a few different variations, including one with a "D" shaped opening and a few that are thinner, longer, have a sharper curve.

• Resize file to where it will fit your particular crab
  • Rotate file so that it's printing from the closed side down to make a good platform to stick on the build plate
  • Print (I suggest having no extra walls and %100 infill but this is an experament so these can gladly be changed)
  • Sand the inside of the shell with low grit sandpaper to remove the bumps
  • Sand the inside with high grit sandpaper to give it a smooth apperance
    5 1/2. If you have it, I highly recomend taking a heat gun used for shrinkwrap and put it on its lowest setting, and LIGHTLY go over the model, mostly pointing at the opening. You don't want the project melting on you now do we?

description.text: This design is used for organization of keys, necklaces, bracelets, and earrings. The holes in the back board are for hanging earrings, the two "T'" shaped structures on the sides are for hanging keys, the two cylinders are for placing bracelets or watches around, and the center tree is used to hang necklaces.

Objectives: Students will be able to explore both creativity and functionality with this design. Students who look at or produce this model will learn the importance of organization and creating correctly scaled pieces to fit the jewelry, watches, an keys being placed on the model.
Audiences: This design may be used for anyone who needs a place to store their things. necklaces may often get tangled and earrings may get lost if they don't have a place to regularly reside, so this would help people of all ages stay organized. 
Preparation: Students should be familiar with the inventor program and comfortable with manipulating the tools in order to create the more expressive design of the tree in the center of the model. 
Steps! : To begin, start a sketch in the XY plane and draw a 2" x 24" rectangle. Starting in the middle of the top of the rectangle, draw a tree that is 2" wide at the base. From there, draw the tree upwards and create enough branches to hold as many necklaces as you would like. Finish the sketch and extrude the rectangle 3" in either direction and extrude the tree whatever thickness you would like in each direction. Fillet the edges of the tree to make it look more realistic. Start a new sketch on the base of the rectangle and draw two circles for the bracelet/watch organizers and then two T shaped holders on either side for keys. Draw a rectangle on the back side of the design with a thickness of .25" and create a rectangular array of small circles across it in order to make holes in which to hang earrings. 
Results: When finished, students will have explored the art of both calculating a precise design and exploring their creative abilities in inventor, and they will be left with a aesthetically pleasing model that can be used to organize.

title: Gill Static Pressure Port for Multi-rotor MAVs

description.text:
Micro aerial vehicles that use a barometric altimeter are often subject to altitude errors due to aerodynamic effects around the airframe. This is most common in rapid horizontal flight. Conventional aircraft avoid this problem with the use of a pitot tube static pressure port. However, multirotors that can move in any of 4 axes need a solution that works in any direction. A disk-shaped static pressure port can accomplish this.
The Gill static pressure port is a type of barometer port that is designed to reduce static pressure measurement errors in high-wind conditions. It does this by decelerating the incoming air, entering at the edge, then isolating the inlet from the flow. These inlets are commonly found on weather stations. The model published here is a scaled-down version, that is small enough and light enough to be practical for use on MAVs.

Printer:

PolyJet HD

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

100%

Notes: The model is designed to sleeve a 5mm tube. It is not a tapered connection. Adhesive should be used. The flight controller will have to be modified to use this pressure port. You can see the method that I used in the discussion thread linked below. In addition, all connections between the port and the flight controller should be completely sealed. Whatever mast this port is mounted on should place the port outside of the airframe's "pressure bubble". That is, the high or low pressure area surrounding it in flight. This may require some experimentation. In the case of my little F450 frame, the mast needs to be fairly tall.

There is precious little information available on how this type of pressure port is supposed to work. I made some educated guesses and performed some simulation to prove the design. Results were really good. It looks like the port relies on boundary-layer effects between the two disks to decelerate incoming air and the cylinder in the middle isolates the actual measurement port from the flow. The result is neutral pressure at the port. This model has been "chunked up" from the original design to make it stronger, more crash-resistant, and printable on desktop FDM machines. The discussion that started the project is here -> http://diydrones.com/forum/topics/effects-of-frame-design-on-barometer-performance-and-all-other?id=705844%3ATopic%3A2071704&page=1#comments The image shows the original design, mounted on a 3mm carbon fiber tube and Hobbyking r/c boat/truck antenna base. 3/32" silicone glow fuel tube is used for connection to the flight controller. An extra bit of silicone tube is used as a flexible coupling to keep the pressure port from breaking off in a crash. It flops around a little, but this doesn't appear to affect its performance.

I don't have any of them currently at home so I can't put the trap into action. I would be pleased if any of you can print it and give any feedback about it and let me know if it works.
It is very simple to use, put some cheese or any other bite inside de trap. When the mouse enters the trap it makes the front door turn and once inside it can't get out of the trap. 
The good thing about this design is that the hinge you can see in the top cover is integrated in it so no assembly work is needed. I always try to design things as simple as possible avoiding complex assemblies which don't usually work when talking about domestic 3D printing.

Update: Small oopsy. I forgot to add the washer to the design. The file has it now but the pictures are not updated. It's just a 1" circle with a 1/4" square cut out. A Simple Perpetual Calendar with space for company logos or whatever strikes your fancy.
Designs are for 1/8" wood.
Very simple to build with minimum gluing, and a clever stand for hanging it. Glue is not really needed for the stand, but recommended for security.
I've given it two sets of dates for 30 or 31 day months, and I put Feb's normal and leap year indicators on the sets.
The real picture is of the 6" version I made with the old stand.
I've tweaked the design a bit so that the max days per month is now on the Month dial.

Assembly: Very simple to assemble.
Sand all the pieces to make sure they're slippery enough.
The Calendar.
Step 1: Glue two bolts ("+" with rounded top) together. Repeat for other bolt.
Step 2: Glue bolts onto the frame with the rounded towards the front. Note: Center hole gets the bolt behind the frame, and the upper hole gets the bolt in front. If needed, sand the backside of the upper bolt so that it's flush.
Step 3: Place the dials on the bolts, apply glue to the arms of the bolts and place the cover/washer to seal them in place.
I shouldn't actually have to tell you which dial goes where and how, do I? The Stand
Step 1: Line up the four pieces in pairs so that they make and almost matching pairs. You can glue them together in this step if you want.
Step 2: Line up the pieces and cross-insert together. There are nubs that will help lock all the pieces together.
You can glue the whole stand along the junctions if you feel the need.

By request. A friend of mine wanted a perpetual calendar, so I started designing in my head. Lots of choices and patterns to decide between. There's the wide one with a frame that slides, the board with movable numbers, and a circular one.
I finally settled on a disc version to save a lot of trouble and space.
There's been four iterations of this one so far, but I think this is the final version. :-)

This is a model I made in Fusion 360 and Meshmixer.
Coral's Song received a National Award from National Scholastic. I made this to resemble a dead/bleached coral and to help share the story of corals. Coral reefs, a vital part of the marine aquatic ecosystem, all around the world are currently dying due to the increase of temperature and acidity in the water. Once these corals die, the ecosystem is ruined and left behind are white, calcium carbonate skeletons. As a Floridian, this is a grave issue that directly affects my local environment. This model is supposed to represent the physical representation of a coral's song asking for help. Please print and share to show your support for the Corals!
